WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.040
You've opened the call, you've taken
control, and you're in the conversation.

2
00:00:05.800 --> 00:00:08.440
Now comes Step 2, the Fact Find.

3
00:00:09.080 --> 00:00:12.340
This is where you'll spend the vast majority
of the call.

4
00:00:13.560 --> 00:00:16.460
The Fact Find is not an interrogation.

5
00:00:16.460 --> 00:00:22.340
It's a conversation. You're genuinely trying
to understand what this person is going

6
00:00:22.340 --> 00:00:26.860
through. And you are listening way more than
you're talking.

7
00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:29.640
You have questions you need to cover, yeah.

8
00:00:29.640 --> 00:00:33.260
But don't fire them off like you're reading
from a clipboard.

9
00:00:33.980 --> 00:00:36.380
Weave them into a natural conversation.

10
00:00:36.740 --> 00:00:40.080
It should feel like two people talking, not
a survey.

11
00:00:41.560 --> 00:00:46.080
For property basics, you want to find out
what type of property it is.

12
00:00:46.500 --> 00:00:49.820
Single family, or duplex, or whatever.

13
00:00:50.260 --> 00:00:52.100
How many bedrooms and bathrooms?

14
00:00:52.620 --> 00:00:54.620
What kind of condition it's in?

15
00:00:54.800 --> 00:00:59.620
And I like to ask them to rate it on a scale
of 1 to 10, because it gives you a

16
00:00:59.620 --> 00:01:03.380
quick picture. And when the last time any
major updates were done?

17
00:01:04.600 --> 00:01:09.440
For ownership and decision making, you want
to confirm they're actually the owner.

18
00:01:10.040 --> 00:01:14.080
Find out if there's anyone else on the title
or involved in the decision.

19
00:01:14.360 --> 00:01:17.620
Ask if there's a mortgage on the property
and roughly what's owed.

20
00:01:18.920 --> 00:01:24.680
For motivation and timeline, you want to know
what's going on with the property that has

21
00:01:24.680 --> 00:01:26.100
them considering selling.

22
00:01:26.420 --> 00:01:29.600
How long they've been thinking about it.
Whether there's a timeline they're working

23
00:01:29.600 --> 00:01:35.680
with. And then this
question, which is one of the most powerful

24
00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:40.120
questions you have. What would happen if you
didn't sell?

25
00:01:41.060 --> 00:01:42.200
What does that look like?

26
00:01:42.580 --> 00:01:47.120
That question forces the seller to
articulate the pain of not taking action.

27
00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:50.840
And that pain? That's what drives deals.

28
00:01:51.340 --> 00:01:53.120
That's what creates urgency.

29
00:01:53.720 --> 00:01:59.580
Don't skip it. Let me talk about energy for
a second, because this matters more than you

30
00:01:59.580 --> 00:01:59.830
probably think.

31
00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:05.620
Your energy on the call matters more than
your words.

32
00:02:06.160 --> 00:02:12.240
If you sound bored or flat or robotic, the
seller will check out in 30 seconds.

33
00:02:12.860 --> 00:02:15.220
Doesn't matter how perfect your script is.

34
00:02:15.500 --> 00:02:20.580
Even if it's your 100th call of the day,
every call should sound like it's your first.

35
00:02:21.380 --> 00:02:24.640
Fresh energy, genuine interest, warmth.

36
00:02:25.220 --> 00:02:26.900
Here's a trick that actually works.

37
00:02:27.340 --> 00:02:29.440
Smile when you talk on the phone.

38
00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:32.060
Literally, physically smile.

39
00:02:32.680 --> 00:02:35.840
I know it sounds weird, but people can hear
it in your voice.

40
00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:39.660
It changes your tone, your pace, everything.

41
00:02:40.300 --> 00:02:44.620
Try it right now. Say, hi, how are you doing
today?

42
00:02:44.640 --> 00:02:48.040
With a flat face. Now say it with a big
smile.

43
00:02:48.480 --> 00:02:50.380
You can hear the difference, right?

44
00:02:50.760 --> 00:02:52.120
Your sellers can too.

45
00:02:53.220 --> 00:02:56.740
A few things I see new people mess up
consistently.

46
00:02:57.420 --> 00:02:59.000
Rushing straight to the property.

47
00:02:59.600 --> 00:03:02.460
Don't jump right into, tell me about the
house.

48
00:03:03.060 --> 00:03:04.480
Build some rapport first.

49
00:03:05.020 --> 00:03:08.560
Find out about them as a person before you
start talking square footage.

50
00:03:08.980 --> 00:03:09.900
Talking too much.

51
00:03:09.900 --> 00:03:13.140
You should be listening 80% of the time.

52
00:03:13.760 --> 00:03:17.700
If you catch yourself going on a monologue,
just stop.

53
00:03:18.060 --> 00:03:21.320
Ask a question. Reading the script like a
robot.

54
00:03:22.040 --> 00:03:25.340
The script is a framework, not a
teleprompter.

55
00:03:25.960 --> 00:03:30.360
Know the beats, know the flow, but deliver
it in your own voice.

56
00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:33.060
If it sounds rehearsed, they're done.

57
00:03:33.660 --> 00:03:35.420
Skipping the pen and paper thing.

58
00:03:35.900 --> 00:03:40.060
I know it seems small, but it sets the tone
for the entire call.

59
00:03:40.520 --> 00:03:42.220
Do it every single time.

60
00:03:42.580 --> 00:03:46.440
And giving up after one weak response.

61
00:03:47.020 --> 00:03:50.860
If they seem short or guarded at first,
that's totally normal.

62
00:03:51.200 --> 00:03:55.020
They've probably been called by five
different people already today.

63
00:03:55.280 --> 00:03:59.580
Be patient, be warm, and give them a reason
to keep talking.

64
00:04:00.660 --> 00:04:03.500
All right, next up, you're going to get your
roleplay.

65
00:04:04.020 --> 00:04:07.560
You're going to practice opening a call with
a warm inbound lead.

66
00:04:08.040 --> 00:04:10.020
Someone who's curious, but a little guarded.

67
00:04:10.560 --> 00:04:12.000
Time to put this stuff to work.
